o formats, the sound of hip hop changed. Drawing from archival research, Amy Coddington shows how the racial organization of the radio industry influenced the way hip hop was sold to the American public, and how the genre's growing popularity transformed ideas about who constitutes the "mainstream."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusic and racezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular musiczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aRadio and musiczUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRap (Music)xHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Rap & Hip Hop.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520383937zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520383937zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520383937/original  a978-3-11-079134-1 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA